Server side, random numbers are generated using: http://php.net/manual/en/function.openssl-random-pseudo-bytes.php

delivery_unsigned_justification: No hash sent over HTTP by default.

name: CII census
description: Automated review of open source software projects
interact_justification: This information is in the README file. The preferred form is pull requests, but we also accept issues and mailing list comments.
contribution_justification: Projects on GitHub by default use issues and pull requests, as encouraged by documentation such as <https://guides.github.com/activities/contributing-to-open-source/>.
contribution_requirements_justification: The [README](https://github.com/linuxfoundation/cii-census/blob/master/README.md) refers to [Python PEP 8](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/), but use 2 spaces per indentation level.
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/linuxfoundation/cii-census/blob/master/LICENSE>.
floss_license_justification: The MIT license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The MIT license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
release_notes_justification: Non-trivial release notes file in repository: <https://github.com/linuxfoundation/cii-census/blob/master/ChangeLog.txt>.
release_notes_vulns_justification: Currently vacuously met, since there are no publicly known vulnerabilities.  But if we have publicly known vulnerabilities, and fix them, then that's the plan.
report_process_justification: The README provides the highlights, which is to report to https://github.com/linuxfoundation/cii-census/issues
report_archive_justification: GitHub issue tracker tracks these at https://github.com/linuxfoundation/cii-census/issues
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: Described at: https://github.com/linuxfoundation/cii-census/blob/master/README.md - email to specific individuals.
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: Described at: https://github.com/linuxfoundation/cii-census/blob/master/README.md - email to specific individuals.
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: Vacuously met; we haven't received any reports.
test_justification: It includes a small set of fixed values and checks, along with expected results, to test the program.
test_invocation_justification: You can invoke the test suite using "make check"; an old but standard way to invoke tests.  This is documented in the README as part of the discussion on providing contributions.
test_most_justification: The program is straightforward, so any test suite will use most of the functionality.  The key difference is that the tests intentionally provide all the data, so there's no reason for the program to make a request over the network to get current data.  However, this difference makes testing much more straightforward.
test_policy_justification: This is the project policy, documented in the
tests_documented_added_justification: This is documented in the README.
warnings_justification: The project enables the "-3" and "-t" warning flags.  This is in addition to use the pyflakes static analyzer.
warnings_strict_justification: Only a few warnings are enabled.
know_secure_design_justification: David A. Wheeler has written a book on how to design an implement secure software, see http://www.dwheeler.com/secure-programs
know_common_errors_justification: David A. Wheeler has written a book on how to implement secure software, see http://www.dwheeler.com/secure-programs
static_analysis_fixed_justification: No such vulnerabilities have been found.
static_analysis_often_justification: It's expected this will be done when we enable continuous integration.
general_comments:
The CII census project predates the badging project.  To get the badge we had to do several things:
* Create an automated test suite, and document the expectation that major changes must extend the test suite to cover that new functionality
* Add a static analysis tool (and fix the problems it identified)
* Document how to report vulnerabilities
* Document the coding conventions used.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: Currently tests are run by developers.  This would be easy to add (just invoke the test suite and analyzer on each commit), we just haven't done it yet.
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
hardened_site_justification: Found all required security hardening headers.
